properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued February 9 at 1:52PM AKST by NWS Juneau AK
properties.description:
Rain re-developing across the central and northern Panhandle Sunday
night will intensify and become heavier into Monday and expand
into the southern Panhandle. Snow levels will also rise to around
2000 feet and higher for much of the Panhandle with the exception
of Upper Lynn Canal. Therefore, melting snow will cause open
rivers to rise through Monday and Monday night. Some rivers with
ice cover may break up allowing levels to rise. In areas of the
northern Panhandle with deeper snow-pack, expect very slick
conditions and potentially significant ponding. To minimize
ponding, keep storm drains clear of snow and ice. Motorists may
experience slick conditions on untreated side streets. Pedestrians
may encounter very hazardous conditions when walking across
melting surfaces. Rain is forecast to exit the Panhandle Monday
evening, but northern Panhandle residents can expect excess melt-
water to re-freeze Tuesday morning extending hazardous
conditions.

NWSheadline: HEAVY RAIN AND HIGH SNOW LEVELS TO CAUSE PONDING AND HIGH RIVER LEVELS
